Attorney General John Ashcroft was cleared of violating anti-lobbying laws for promoting the Patriot Act in speeches.
The Act, passed after 9/11, expanded law enforcement powers against terrorists.
President Bush praised Ashcroft's efforts in counterterrorism.
Critics argue the Act infringes on civil liberties, with concerns over surveillance and secret searches.
A coalition of groups, including the ACLU and conservative libertarians, seeks to repeal certain provisions.
The debate over renewing the Patriot Act highlights the balance between security and freedom.
Calls for amendments to protect rights while combating terrorism are gaining momentum.
